WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.44
This is Jockelpontcast number 214.

2
00:00:03.44 --> 00:00:06.44
With echo Charles and me, Jockel Willink.

3
00:00:06.44 --> 00:00:07.44
Good evening, echo.

4
00:00:07.44 --> 00:00:08.44
Good evening.

5
00:00:08.44 --> 00:00:14.48
Dear George, at 0700 this morning,

6
00:00:14.48 --> 00:00:18.68
the BBC announced that the German radio had just come out

7
00:00:18.68 --> 00:00:23.12
with an announcement of the landing of Allied paratroops

8
00:00:23.12 --> 00:00:26.64
and of large numbers of assault craft near the shore.

9
00:00:26.64 --> 00:00:29.000
So that is it.

10
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.32
This group of unconscribable heroes

11
00:00:33.32 --> 00:00:37.64
whom I command are not in yet, but we will be soon.

12
00:00:37.64 --> 00:00:41.64
I wish I was there now as it is a lovely sunny day for battle

13
00:00:41.64 --> 00:00:44.60
and I am fed up with just sitting.

14
00:00:44.60 --> 00:00:47.88
I have no immediate idea of being killed,

15
00:00:47.88 --> 00:00:50.80
but one can never tell and none of us can live forever.

16
00:00:50.80 --> 00:00:54.44
So if I should go, don't worry, but set yourself

17
00:00:54.44 --> 00:00:57.000
to do better than I have.

18
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.24
All men are timid on entering any fight.

19
00:01:00.24 --> 00:01:03.52
Whether it is the first fight or the last fight,

20
00:01:03.52 --> 00:01:06.08
all of us are timid.

21
00:01:06.08 --> 00:01:08.60
Cowards are those who let their timidity

22
00:01:08.60 --> 00:01:10.80
get the better of their manhood.

23
00:01:12.08 --> 00:01:14.76
You will never do that because of your bloodlines

24
00:01:14.76 --> 00:01:16.92
on both sides.

25
00:01:16.92 --> 00:01:20.64
I think I've told you the story of Marshall Torraine

26
00:01:20.64 --> 00:01:24.64
who fought under Louis XIV.

27
00:01:24.64 --> 00:01:27.68
On the morning of one of his last battles,

28
00:01:27.68 --> 00:01:29.56
he had been fighting for 40 years.

29
00:01:29.56 --> 00:01:31.72
He was mounting his horse when a young aide

30
00:01:31.72 --> 00:01:34.28
to camp who had just come from the court

31
00:01:34.28 --> 00:01:37.36
and had never missed a meal or heard a hostile shot.

32
00:01:37.36 --> 00:01:40.60
Said Mr. Torraine, it amazes me

33
00:01:40.60 --> 00:01:42.80
that a man of your supposed courage

34
00:01:42.80 --> 00:01:45.16
should permit his knees to tremble

35
00:01:45.16 --> 00:01:46.92
as he walks out to Mount.

36
00:01:48.16 --> 00:01:49.56
Torraine replied,

37
00:01:49.56 --> 00:01:52.68
my Lord Duke, I admit that my Nate knees do tremble.

38
00:01:52.68 --> 00:01:57.68
But should they know where I shall this day take them,

39
00:01:57.68 --> 00:01:59.72
they would shake even more?

40
00:02:01.52 --> 00:02:03.04
That is it.

41
00:02:03.04 --> 00:02:04.84
Your knees may shake,

42
00:02:04.84 --> 00:02:07.60
but they will always take you toward the enemy.

43
00:02:08.92 --> 00:02:10.44
Well, so much for that.

44
00:02:10.44 --> 00:02:13.72
There are apparently two types of successful soldiers.

45
00:02:13.72 --> 00:02:17.000
Those who get on by being unobtrusive

46
00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:19.68
and those who get on by being obtrusive.

47
00:02:19.68 --> 00:02:24.16
I am of the latter type and seem to be rare

48
00:02:24.16 --> 00:02:26.92
and unpopular, but it is my method.

49
00:02:26.92 --> 00:02:30.04
One has to choose a system and stick to it.

50
00:02:30.04 --> 00:02:34.52
People who are not themselves are nobody.

51
00:02:35.80 --> 00:02:40.68
To be a successful soldier, you must know history.

52
00:02:40.68 --> 00:02:43.20
Read it objectively.

53
00:02:43.20 --> 00:02:48.000
Dates and even the minute details of tactics are useless.

54
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.000
What you must know is how man reacts.

55
00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:59.000
Weapons change, but man who uses them changes not at all.

56
00:03:01.56 --> 00:03:04.20
To win battles, you do not beat weapons.

57
00:03:04.20 --> 00:03:07.76
You beat the soul of man of the enemy.

58
00:03:10.56 --> 00:03:13.08
To do that, you have to destroy his weapons,

59
00:03:13.08 --> 00:03:15.52
but that is only incidental.

60
00:03:15.52 --> 00:03:16.92
You must read biography

61
00:03:16.92 --> 00:03:18.80
and especially autobiography.

62
00:03:19.80 --> 00:03:24.000
If you do that, it will, you will find that war is simple.

63
00:03:25.20 --> 00:03:27.56
Decide what will hurt the enemy most

64
00:03:27.56 --> 00:03:30.000
within the limits of your capabilities to harm him

65
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:31.04
and then do it.

66
00:03:32.52 --> 00:03:34.92
Take calculated risks.

67
00:03:34.92 --> 00:03:37.12
That is quite different from being rash.

68
00:03:37.12 --> 00:03:41.12
My personal belief is that if you have a 50% chance,

69
00:03:41.12 --> 00:03:44.04
take it because of the superior fighting qualities

70
00:03:44.04 --> 00:03:47.20
of American soldiers lead me, led by me,

71
00:03:47.20 --> 00:03:50.88
will surely give you the extra 1% necessary.

72
00:03:52.20 --> 00:03:54.84
Incidentally, I decided as a result of my information

73
00:03:54.84 --> 00:03:57.92
observations and a sixth sense that I have

74
00:03:57.92 --> 00:04:00.24
that the enemy did not have another large scale

75
00:04:00.24 --> 00:04:01.72
attack in his system.

76
00:04:02.76 --> 00:04:05.28
I bet my shirt on that and I was right.

77
00:04:06.36 --> 00:04:10.36
You cannot make war safely, but no dead general

78
00:04:10.36 --> 00:04:12.68
has ever been criticized.

79
00:04:12.68 --> 00:04:15.08
So you have that way out always.

80
00:04:16.80 --> 00:04:19.88
I am sure that if every leader who goes into battle

81
00:04:19.88 --> 00:04:22.60
will promise himself that he will either come out

82
00:04:22.60 --> 00:04:26.88
a conqueror or a corpse, he is sure to win.

83
00:04:28.28 --> 00:04:29.72
There is no doubt of that.

84
00:04:31.24 --> 00:04:33.72
Defeat is not due to losses,

85
00:04:33.72 --> 00:04:37.60
but to the destruction of the soul of the leaders.

86
00:04:37.60 --> 00:04:42.60
The most vital quality a soldier can possess

87
00:04:47.04 --> 00:04:52.20
is self-confidence, utter, complete and bumpuous.

88
00:04:52.20 --> 00:04:54.08
You can have doubts about your good looks,

89
00:04:54.08 --> 00:04:56.60
about your intelligence, about your self-control,

90
00:04:56.60 --> 00:04:59.24
but to win in war, you must have no doubts

91
00:04:59.24 --> 00:05:01.24
about your ability as a soldier.

92
00:05:03.08 --> 00:05:06.08
What success I have had results from the fact

93
00:05:06.08 --> 00:05:08.16
that I have always been certain that my military

94
00:05:08.16 --> 00:05:09.72
reactions were correct.

95
00:05:11.12 --> 00:05:13.16
Many people do not agree with me.

96
00:05:13.16 --> 00:05:14.32
They are wrong.

97
00:05:15.60 --> 00:05:20.000
The un-airing jury of history written long after both of us

98
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
are dead will prove me correct.

99
00:05:23.16 --> 00:05:26.36
Note that I speak of military reactions.

100
00:05:26.36 --> 00:05:28.96
No one is born with them anymore than anyone is born

101
00:05:28.96 --> 00:05:30.000
with muscles.

102
00:05:31.24 --> 00:05:34.52
You can be born with the soul capable of correct military

103
00:05:34.52 --> 00:05:38.48
reactions or the body capable of having big muscles,

104
00:05:38.48 --> 00:05:42.56
but both qualities must be developed by hard work.

105
00:05:44.68 --> 00:05:46.84
The intensity of your desire to acquire

106
00:05:46.84 --> 00:05:50.48
any special ability depends on character, on ambition.

107
00:05:51.68 --> 00:05:53.64
I think that your decision to study this summer

108
00:05:53.64 --> 00:05:55.52
instead of enjoying yourself shows

109
00:05:55.52 --> 00:05:57.44
that you have character and ambition.

110
00:05:58.64 --> 00:06:01.32
And they are wonderful possessions.

111
00:06:01.32 --> 00:06:06.32
Soldiers, all men in fact are natural hero worshippers.

112
00:06:07.68 --> 00:06:11.20
Officers with a flare for command realize this

113
00:06:11.20 --> 00:06:15.000
and emphasize in their conduct, dress and deportment.

114
00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.36
The qualities they seek to produce in their men.

115
00:06:20.64 --> 00:06:22.48
When I was a second lieutenant,

116
00:06:22.48 --> 00:06:25.92
I had a captain who was very sloppy and usually late.

117
00:06:25.92 --> 00:06:30.16
He got after his men for just those faults.

118
00:06:30.16 --> 00:06:32.76
He was a failure.

119
00:06:32.76 --> 00:06:37.36
The troops I have commanded have always been well dressed,

120
00:06:37.36 --> 00:06:40.60
been smart saluters, been prompt and bold and action

121
00:06:40.60 --> 00:06:44.28
because I have personally set the example in these qualities.

122
00:06:44.28 --> 00:06:48.28
The influence one man can have on thousands

123
00:06:48.28 --> 00:06:50.92
is a never-ending source of wonder to me.

124
00:06:50.92 --> 00:06:53.60
You are always on parade.

125
00:06:53.60 --> 00:06:58.60
Officers who through laziness or a foolish desire

126
00:06:59.16 --> 00:07:02.56
to be popular fail to enforce discipline

127
00:07:02.56 --> 00:07:05.000
and the proper wearing of uniforms and equipment,

128
00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:06.72
not in the presence of the enemy,

129
00:07:06.72 --> 00:07:09.08
will also fail in battle.

130
00:07:11.36 --> 00:07:15.24
And if they fail in battle, they are potential mergers.

131
00:07:17.60 --> 00:07:20.76
There is no such thing as a good field soldier.

132
00:07:20.76 --> 00:07:24.60
You are either a good soldier or a bad soldier.

133
00:07:26.84 --> 00:07:29.12
Well, this has been quite a sermon,

134
00:07:30.12 --> 00:07:33.44
but don't get the idea that it is my swan song

135
00:07:33.44 --> 00:07:34.56
because it is not.

136
00:07:36.92 --> 00:07:40.40
I have not finished my job yet.

137
00:07:42.12 --> 00:07:45.40
Signed your affectionate father.

138
00:07:47.36 --> 00:07:49.16
And that right there, if you haven't guessed

139
00:07:49.16 --> 00:07:52.24
as a letter from General George S. Patent

140
00:07:52.24 --> 00:07:55.44
to his son, the George as the day unfolded.

141
00:07:57.88 --> 00:08:01.48
And as you can see from the letter

142
00:08:01.48 --> 00:08:03.28
and also if you know anything about Patent,

143
00:08:03.28 --> 00:08:07.56
at all he was well known, not only for his skill and battle

144
00:08:07.56 --> 00:08:12.56
and as a tactician and as a leader, but also well known

145
00:08:12.56 --> 00:08:13.56
for his ego.

146
00:08:15.60 --> 00:08:17.000
Let me read this part again.

147
00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:19.36
The most vital quality a soldier can possess

148
00:08:19.36 --> 00:08:22.76
his self confidence, utter complete and bump to us.

149
00:08:24.12 --> 00:08:29.12
And what bump truss means is is proud to a degree

150
00:08:29.84 --> 00:08:30.96
where it's irritating.

151
00:08:30.96 --> 00:08:32.96
So it means what it sounds like, right?

152
00:08:32.96 --> 00:08:34.92
And he's saying that's how you need to be.

153
00:08:34.92 --> 00:08:37.40
He continues on, you can have doubts about your good looks

154
00:08:37.40 --> 00:08:39.56
about your intelligence, about your self control,

155
00:08:39.56 --> 00:08:41.32
but to win in war you must have no doubts

156
00:08:41.32 --> 00:08:43.44
about your ability as a soldier.

157
00:08:43.44 --> 00:08:47.92
What success I have had results from the fact

158
00:08:47.92 --> 00:08:49.96
that I have always been certain

159
00:08:49.96 --> 00:08:52.96
that my military reactions were correct.

160
00:08:52.96 --> 00:08:54.76
Many people do not agree with me, they are wrong.

161
00:08:54.76 --> 00:08:59.76
Now, that's obviously very contrary to what I think,

162
00:09:02.96 --> 00:09:06.64
which is the most important characteristic

163
00:09:06.64 --> 00:09:09.44
for a leader to have is humility.

164
00:09:09.44 --> 00:09:12.68
So we're actually saying the exact opposite things here.

165
00:09:12.68 --> 00:09:14.40
I mean straight up the opposite things.

166
00:09:14.40 --> 00:09:16.52
He's saying the most important thing is self confidence,

167
00:09:16.52 --> 00:09:17.88
but he doesn't say self confidence.

168
00:09:17.88 --> 00:09:20.96
He says utter and complete and bump truss.

169
00:09:20.96 --> 00:09:22.20
That's what he says.

170
00:09:22.20 --> 00:09:23.88
That's not, that's not humility.

171
00:09:25.96 --> 00:09:29.32
So where does this wash out?

172
00:09:32.24 --> 00:09:36.60
We have to remember that the patent's career was not unblumished.

173
00:09:36.60 --> 00:09:39.04
And this is the thing that I'm gonna keep kind of tying

174
00:09:39.04 --> 00:09:39.88
this back to.

175
00:09:41.12 --> 00:09:42.60
A lot of the things that I think

176
00:09:42.60 --> 00:09:44.64
you remember when we did

177
00:09:46.32 --> 00:09:49.28
Chairman Mao and we talked about

178
00:09:49.28 --> 00:09:53.72
Chairman Mao and his methodology for winning in guerrilla war.

179
00:09:53.72 --> 00:09:56.28
And everything that he said,

180
00:09:57.96 --> 00:10:00.68
well, it wasn't like aligned with what I say.

181
00:10:00.68 --> 00:10:02.56
And what are the key components of that?

182
00:10:02.56 --> 00:10:04.44
Maybe not everything, but a lot of what he was saying

183
00:10:04.44 --> 00:10:05.72
and I'd have to review it again,

184
00:10:05.72 --> 00:10:07.000
but a lot of what he was saying,

185
00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.12
but one thing that he absolutely said,

186
00:10:10.12 --> 00:10:15.12
Chairman Mao, father of communist China,

187
00:10:16.60 --> 00:10:19.84
said all throughout that the leaders in the field

188
00:10:19.84 --> 00:10:22.04
need to make decisions, they need to step up,

189
00:10:22.04 --> 00:10:23.92
they need to lead at what he's talking about

190
00:10:23.92 --> 00:10:25.000
his decentralized command.

191
00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.08
And what puzzles me about that is

192
00:10:27.08 --> 00:10:30.96
because he recognized that you needed to have decentralized

193
00:10:30.96 --> 00:10:35.16
command for a military victory, right to win.

194
00:10:35.16 --> 00:10:38.32
But then he never transposed that idea

195
00:10:38.32 --> 00:10:40.64
of decentralized command into his government.

196
00:10:40.64 --> 00:10:44.04
And we actually do know that centralized government

197
00:10:44.04 --> 00:10:47.24
doesn't work any better than centralized military

198
00:10:47.24 --> 00:10:49.20
command than centralized business leadership.

199
00:10:49.20 --> 00:10:50.04
It doesn't work.

200
00:10:51.20 --> 00:10:53.56
So he never made that connection apparently.

201
00:10:54.72 --> 00:10:56.36
And sometimes when I read about patent,

202
00:10:56.36 --> 00:10:57.64
if you know about patent,

203
00:10:59.04 --> 00:11:00.40
and you know about his career

204
00:11:00.40 --> 00:11:02.40
and you know what happened to him,

205
00:11:02.40 --> 00:11:07.28
sometimes you, it hurts a little bit to know

206
00:11:07.28 --> 00:11:10.08
that this guy who was such a great patriot,

207
00:11:10.08 --> 00:11:11.64
who was such a great tactician,

208
00:11:11.64 --> 00:11:14.36
that if he could have applied some of his principles

209
00:11:14.36 --> 00:11:15.80
of leadership on the battlefield,

210
00:11:15.80 --> 00:11:20.04
if he could have applied those to his interactions

211
00:11:20.04 --> 00:11:23.40
with other people, he might have ended up

212
00:11:23.40 --> 00:11:24.92
in a much better position.

213
00:11:27.08 --> 00:11:28.24
And we'll get into some of that.

214
00:11:28.24 --> 00:11:31.36
Some of the things that he did,

215
00:11:31.36 --> 00:11:37.32
one, there was an attack on a place called Fort Giante,

216
00:11:37.32 --> 00:11:38.64
in the fall of 1944.

217
00:11:38.64 --> 00:11:41.08
And I got this little, I wanted to kind of summarize it.

218
00:11:41.08 --> 00:11:44.56
And there's a thing called the warfare history network

219
00:11:44.56 --> 00:11:46.08
that summarized it very well.

220
00:11:46.08 --> 00:11:48.36
It said the entire operation gradually settled

221
00:11:48.36 --> 00:11:50.60
into a stalemate with the Americans

222
00:11:50.60 --> 00:11:52.84
unable to achieve any further gains

223
00:11:52.84 --> 00:11:54.72
and the men hanging on desperately

224
00:11:54.72 --> 00:11:57.12
to what had been won in the hard fighting.

225
00:11:57.12 --> 00:11:59.52
Food, water, and ammunition were running out

226
00:11:59.52 --> 00:12:02.04
and the men holding positions underground

227
00:12:02.04 --> 00:12:05.24
were exposed to the dust and fumes of the tunnels

228
00:12:05.24 --> 00:12:08.60
by October 9th, Patent's attitude about the attack

229
00:12:08.60 --> 00:12:10.96
had changed completely.

230
00:12:10.96 --> 00:12:14.36
He said the show is going sour, we will have to pull out.

231
00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.96
It had quickly become a no win situation for the Americans

232
00:12:18.96 --> 00:12:22.48
because both daylight and nocturnal salts had failed.

233
00:12:22.48 --> 00:12:24.72
Daytime attacks were vulnerable to the deadly fire

234
00:12:24.72 --> 00:12:28.68
that rained down on Fort Giante from the adjacent forts

235
00:12:28.68 --> 00:12:30.84
at night assaults were quickly broken up

236
00:12:30.84 --> 00:12:33.12
and driven into confusion when the German squads

237
00:12:33.12 --> 00:12:35.28
emerged from their underground tunnels.

238
00:12:35.28 --> 00:12:39.82
The third army suffered 64 men killed 547 wounded,

239
00:12:39.82 --> 00:12:43.36
187 missing assumed captured,

240
00:12:43.36 --> 00:12:45.68
so and not achieving the objective.

241
00:12:45.68 --> 00:12:48.68
So that's not good, right?

242
00:12:48.68 --> 00:12:52.36
So the idea to think that everything I think of is correct.

243
00:12:54.68 --> 00:12:57.32
And there you go, even Patent, guess what he had to do?

244
00:12:57.32 --> 00:12:59.92
He had to go, okay, this isn't working.

